##The death cases of new coronary disease are a "complex" to find the answer —— An interview with Professor Qiu Haibo of the medical treatment Expert Group of the National Health Commission

Micro Signal Xinminzhoukan

Function description, depth and angle —— this is what we can do.

Dictation Line

Although it looks like we used both inhalation support and ECMO support, we didn't get it back, but we used it too late. From these lessons we know that the treatment threshold has to move forward.

Reporter | Huang Qi

Recently, Professor Qiu Haibo, Deputy Secretary of the Party Committee of the Zhongda Hospital affiliated to Southeast University, who has been working on the front line in Wuhan for more than 40 days, completed the fifth round of inspection by the Medical Treatment Expert Group of the National Health Commission. Every medical institution, Professor Qiu Haibo will be responsible for the treatment of new severe pneumonia together with colleagues, discuss the treatment of difficult patients, especially the death cases, to a "reset. ".

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Professor Qiu Haibo put forward "silent hypoxemia" and other important judgments in the early stage of the epidemic to provide evidence for the improvement of follow-up treatment

Professor Qiu Haibo said the new pneumonia outbreak was the most serious infectious disease outbreak since the founding of the People's Republic of China, and although Wuhan is a city rich in medical resources, it still suffered huge losses under heavy pressure.

NEW PNEUMONIA is a new disease, in addition, the virus transmission ability is too strong, the early patients make medical treatment into a dilemma, as a result, the medical treatment of severe patients increased rapidly, the success rate is low, to bring panic to society.

With the help of the national medical team and the arrival of rescue materials, as well as the opening of the Shelter Hospital and the strengthening of community management, in the late stage of the epidemic, the success rate of the treatment of critically ill patients gradually increased.

Nearly two months on, Wuhan is beginning to see the light of day, one of the best predictions yet.

Severe medical professionals play an important role in the treatment of severe cases of new coronary pneumonia in Wuhan. More than 11,000 doctors and nurses from all over the country are treating the most severe cases of new coronavirus pneumonia in Wuhan.

Professor Qiu Haibo is the first doctor of critical care medicine in China. Since the SARS epidemic in 2003, the 2005 Streptococcus suis epidemic, the 2009 H1N1 influenza epidemic, the 2013 H7N9 bird flu epidemic... in every major public health emergency, he is not only directly involved in the treatment of patients as an expert in critical care medicine, it also provides a wealth of important advice for decision-making and treatment. In the new crown pneumonia epidemic situation, Professor Qiu Haibo also many times in the expert meeting to the Central Steering Group leadership put forward the important decision-making proposal.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Professor Qiu Haibo (right) and Peking Union Medical College Hospital, an expert in critical care medicine, lunch in Wuhan

"there are still thousands of new pneumonia patients in hospitals in Wuhan, and hundreds of seriously ill patients who are not out of danger. " As people in many parts of the country began to relieve the pressure, Professor Qiu Haibo remained the same as all medical staff, never let your guard down.

While treating patients, Professor Qiu Haibo summed up the enlightenment brought by the epidemic. On the afternoon of March 9, Professor Qiu Haibo gave an interview to Xinmin Weekly.

Experience in the treatment of severe patients with "restoring disk"

Xinmin Weekly: All the shelter hospitals in Wuhan are closed, and the designated hospital beds are also beginning to be vacated. Can it be said that the epidemic in Wuhan has been greatly alleviated?

Qiu Haibo: please don't misunderstand the shelter hospital. The rest of the cabin is not permanently closed, next Wuhan will gradually start to resume production, the city will gradually open, if there are any additional cases of patients in the future, can always open these shelter hospitals. Look at the current situation, fixed-point hospital beds out of the free, the Shelter Hospital this temporary, simple hospital can be temporarily not used.

Before Wuhan almost all the hospitals are used to treat new coronary pneumonia patients, now fixed-point hospital, some ward closed. Some hospitals ICU beds half empty, beds oversupply, is a very happy phenomenon. I know of medical teams that arrive late to replace those that arrive early, and some of the medical staff can be rotated out.

These are all signs that the epidemic is in remission. Hospitals in Wuhan will gradually resume normal medical services for patients with tumors, chronic kidney failure and other acute cases such as heart attack, cerebral infarction, cholecystitis and appendicitis.

"Xinmin Weekly" : The National Health Commission Medical Treatment Expert Group completed the fifth round of inspection, this inspection is mainly for what purpose?

Qiu Haibo: The public is very concerned about the case fatality rate of NCP, which is also the special concern of our expert group. The focus of the fifth round of inspection is to bring out the cases of previous deaths for discussion, one by one, "reset. ". We hope to learn from the experience of these treatment, to find better treatment experience, reduce the mortality rate of critically ill patients.

We have used some good experience before, such as "moving forward" , some treatment measures to be used earlier, the effect will be better.

But we should also objectively see that the new crown pneumonia epidemic is the most serious epidemic after the establishment of new China, the virus spread too fast. Wuhan is rich in medical resources, we assume that the outbreak in Beijing, Shanghai, I am afraid to face similar treatment pressure. Therefore, the early mortality rate is relatively high, and the characteristics of the virus itself.

In the 2003 SARS epidemic, there were only a few thousand patients in the country. The new crown pneumonia epidemic, 2 months time has more than 80,000 patients, early even if there are medical teams all over the country to support, treatment is still very tight.

Xinmin Weekly: What problems do you see in the course of the "reset" ?

Qiu Haibo: in the early treatment of patients with severe illness, some measures may be problematic. For example, some patients have a cardiac arrest on intubation, how can this be true? It must have been too late to intubate. At this time the patient's heart, kidneys and so on have been damaged by lack of oxygen. The time of non-invasive ventilation is too long and the time of intubation is too late for some severe patients in early stage.

In the early days of the epidemic, we had these problems because of the limited treatment conditions, and many patients left us with very painful lessons. And then when we were ready, we were supposed to follow protocol.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Professor Qiu Haibo (first right) and du Bin, Guan Xiangdong, and other domestic authorities in the new severe pneumonia ward work together

Xinmin Weekly: You arrived in Wuhan on January 20. What is the state of early treatment?

Qiu Haibo: You can also see some of the early stages of the epidemic in the media. At that time the patient Mengzeng, a bed hard to get, the hospital ICU beds full, intensive care received countless calls: This patient is not, can not be admitted? But the ICU couldn't do it, couldn't get it in. In this case, the bed must be expanded, 20,30 pieces of no use, out of the room immediately full.

In view of this situation, our expert group recommended to the Central Guidance Group that we should rapidly increase the number of designated hospitals for intensive care patients and rapidly expand the number of intensive care beds, and this suggestion was quickly adopted.

The requisitioned hospital was turned into an entire ward for the seriously ill, but beds were no use, when medical teams from all over the country came to help. Nor has it ever been the case that more than a dozen hospitals have been requisitioned to treat all patients with infectious diseases.

Xinmin Weekly: Is there an objective reason why it was too late to intubate some of the early patients?

Qiu Haibo: during the early outbreak, there were too many critical patients, not enough beds in the ICU, patients could not enter the ICU and could not be intubated. In addition, even if you can do intubation, the first few days of oxygen pressure is not enough, equipment is not in place, intubation is useless. The other reason is, in the early days, our doctors didn't have enough protection, or they didn't have it, or they didn't have enough protection, how do you tell them to intubate?

Paramedics are scared, too. During SARS in 2003, many medical workers inserted tubes into patients without proper protection, causing infection.

Of course, we later discovered that some non-critical care physicians also had misconceptions about the risk of infection from intubated ventilation. Some doctors believe that the risk of infection for health care workers is higher than that for non invasive ventilation, but it is not. The gas flow rate of non invasive ventilation is much higher than that of intubation ventilation, and in theory the risk of infection is higher.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Professor Qiu Haibo organized the treatment of severe patients

Xinmin Weekly: After 30 years of intensive care, you saw a lot of life and death. How did you feel in the first few days in Wuhan?

Qiu Haibo: Some people say that doctors have an "emotional filter. " Many people think that we doctors face death every day, so it doesn't matter if we see a patient die. Actually, no. Doctors are human beings, too, and they get desperate when they can't.

When I first got here, I was on rounds at night, and the next day, three patients were gone. Am I okay with this? It's totally unacceptable. It's devastating. Why is this happening? At that time a lot of treatment conditions are not, the patient needs oxygen, but oxygen pressure is not enough, the machine can not play. I reflected these difficulties up to the Central Guidance Group, and later all these problems were solved.

Doctors can't bring all the patients back, but we all want to do our best to save the patients.

Understanding of new coronary pneumonia: silent hypoxemia

"The Xinmin Weekly" : You proposed very early, the new coronary pneumonia characteristic is "the silent hypoxemia" , afterward looked back then these serious patients, whether confirmed then the judgment?

Qiu Haibo: Yes. We often hear the clinician say that the patient was fine the day before and suddenly he is not. I've seen this in patients before.

In severe cases like the one we've had, if he Oxygenation down, you feel sick, you hold your breath, your heart rate increases. Anyone who's ever been to Tibet has experienced it, the lack of oxygen on the plateau, the pounding of your heart. With these symptoms, the doctor will go to timely blood oxygen test, timely treatment for him, to solve the problem of Oxygenation.

But the new coronary pneumonia patient, his own chief complaint is not obvious, that is to say he did not feel too uncomfortable, he will say that a little suffocated, but not too serious. If the doctor took a test at this time, he would find that his oxygen saturation is actually very low. This is what I call silent hypoxemia.

In the early days, we did not know enough about this phenomenon, and some treatments were used too late, such as intubation and ventilation, until it was too late to be used. This is how we learn about a new disease.

Xinmin Weekly: How hard is it to figure out how to treat severe cases of new coronary pneumonia?

Qiu Haibo: the first month of trying to figure out a treatment was quite difficult.

We found some very effective measures. For example, I proposed the "prone position ventilation" method, let the patient lie on his stomach, "prone position ventilation" can use gravity to drain the secretion in the patient's trachea, for the patient's oxygen saturation recovery is helpful.

Xinmin Weekly: What do you mean by "crossing forward" ?

Qiu Haibo: When we say "the threshold is moving forward" , we mean to find the key point in the process of changing from mild to severe, from severe to severe, and to cut off this development in a timely manner. Especially in critically ill patients, we found that the new coronavirus harm to the human body, involving the lungs, heart, intestines and other important organs, it should be considered as "new coronavirus infection. ". Both the control of lung symptoms and other organ symptoms need to be moved forward.

Critical care isn't strong enough

Xinmin Weekly: What role did the NMHC team of medical experts play in the new crown pneumonia epidemic?

Qiu Haibo: the panel has several roles. The first is to the ward as a medical team leader, leadership and participation in the treatment of critically ill patients. The second is to guide treatment, we have a regular inspection system, to each treatment group to see some key patients, case discussion, Research Treatment Program. The third is a very important task: We go through rounds, see patients, sum up the experience and lessons of treatment, to sum up these clinical experience into the new coronary pneumonia diagnosis and treatment program.

So far the protocol has been updated to the seventh edition, and the efficiency is very high.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Professor Qiu Haibo during the day in the hospital to guide treatment, night to sum up experience and exchange with experts in the same field

Xinmin Weekly: What lessons do you think we should draw from this outbreak?

Qiu Haibo: I'm a clinician. My job is to treat patients. If after an infectious disease outbreak, all expectations are placed in the ICU, the ICU, the last line of Defense of life, to put pressure on this place, it is the worst. The best way to deal with the epidemic situation of infectious diseases is to do a good job of prevention and control first. On this basis, we should cure those who are sick.

If prevention and control are done well, the number of patients will not be so many, the patient base is small, then the severe cases will be fewer, and the mortality rate will not be so high. So I think we have to strengthen public health in the future.

Xinmin Weekly: From the point of view of treatment, what are the implications?

Qiu Haibo: from the point of view of treatment, we all had contingency plans for public health emergencies in the past, but when such a large epidemic occurred, we found that the previous contingency plans did not work. It means we're not high enough to take into account the severity of the situation.

I think top-level planning for public health emergencies. For example, if a low-intensity infectious disease epidemic, how to deal with; medium-intensity Infectious Disease Epidemic, how to deal with; high-intensity Infectious Disease Epidemic, how to do. We need to plan for an epidemic on several levels.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
More than 10,000 doctors and nurses from the major of critical care medicine, accounting for one-third of all medical support staff, are taking part in the treatment in Hubei

Xinmin Weekly: You are an expert in critical care medicine. More than 10,000 critical care doctors and nurses from all over the country are assisting Wuhan in the outbreak. Why do you think the reserve of critical care medical talents is not enough?

Qiu Haibo: Hubei Support of the critical care medical personnel, accounting for about 10% of the national critical care medical personnel. In the medical teams from all over the country, there are doctors from all departments in Wuhan. We have found that it is especially difficult for doctors from other departments to treat patients with severe illness. They're willing to kill, but they don't have enough weapons. The treatment of seriously ill patients, can not rely on passion, must be technology and methods, and these technologies are not short-term training can learn.

Recently, I suggested to the relevant leaders of the National Health Commission that critical care medicine should be included in the training system for residents. Critical Care Medicine is the only secondary discipline that has not been incorporated into the resident training system. We only have specialist training, and only train a few hundred people a year nationally.

It's like a pyramid. We have people at the top of the pyramid, but there's no training system at the bottom of the pyramid. The discipline has no foundation.
